<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="105" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1670,1947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1670,1695]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[282,481,1670,1694]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Ptilomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jariyae">
<emphasis box="[282,481,1670,1694]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Ptilomera jariyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males can be recognized by the well-developed median lobe of the proctiger (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 23. Terminal abdominal segments of male Ptilomera. P. fang in (10) dorsal and (11) ventral view; P. hemmingseni in (12) dorsal and (13) ventral view; P. hylactor in (14) dorsal and (15) ventral view; P. jariyae in (16) dorsal and (17) ventral view; P. k r a in (18) dorsal and (19) ventral view; P. tennaserim in (20) dorsal and (21) ventral view; P. tigrina in (22) dorsal and (23) ventral view. Figs. 20 – 21 are of holotype prior to extraction of genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230503/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Figs. 16, 17</figureCitation>
), and females by the absence of a ventrolateral lobe of abdominal segment VII (
<figureCitation box="[1202,1350,1706,1731]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 37" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1584,1607]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1561]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1563]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 37. Terminal abdominal segments of female Ptilomera. P. fang in (24) dorsal and (25) lateral view; P. hemmingseni in (26) dorsal and (27) lateral view; P. hylactor in (28) dorsal and (29) lateral view; P. j ar i y ae in (30) dorsal and (31) lateral view; P. k r a in (32) dorsal and (33) lateral view; P. tennaserim in (34) dorsal and (35) lateral view; P. tigrina in (36) dorsal and (37) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230504/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Figs. 30, 31</figureCitation>
). More specifically, males of 
<emphasis box="[408,516,1743,1766]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">P. j a r i y a e</emphasis>
can be distinguished by the median lobe of the proctiger well surpassing the posterior tips of the lateral wings (
<figureCitation box="[550,635,1778,1803]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 23. Terminal abdominal segments of male Ptilomera. P. fang in (10) dorsal and (11) ventral view; P. hemmingseni in (12) dorsal and (13) ventral view; P. hylactor in (14) dorsal and (15) ventral view; P. jariyae in (16) dorsal and (17) ventral view; P. k r a in (18) dorsal and (19) ventral view; P. tennaserim in (20) dorsal and (21) ventral view; P. tigrina in (22) dorsal and (23) ventral view. Figs. 20 – 21 are of holotype prior to extraction of genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230503/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Fig. 
<number box="[605,635,1778,1803]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
), whereas it is more or less even with the posterior tips of the lateral wings in 
<taxonomicName box="[259,365,1815,1838]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Ptilomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrina">
<emphasis box="[259,273,1815,1838]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[289,365,1815,1838]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">tigrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[383,469,1814,1839]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 23. Terminal abdominal segments of male Ptilomera. P. fang in (10) dorsal and (11) ventral view; P. hemmingseni in (12) dorsal and (13) ventral view; P. hylactor in (14) dorsal and (15) ventral view; P. jariyae in (16) dorsal and (17) ventral view; P. k r a in (18) dorsal and (19) ventral view; P. tennaserim in (20) dorsal and (21) ventral view; P. tigrina in (22) dorsal and (23) ventral view. Figs. 20 – 21 are of holotype prior to extraction of genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230503/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Fig. 
<number box="[438,469,1815,1839]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
), and by the pygophore with a roundly triangular apex (
<figureCitation box="[1120,1205,1814,1839]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 23. Terminal abdominal segments of male Ptilomera. P. fang in (10) dorsal and (11) ventral view; P. hemmingseni in (12) dorsal and (13) ventral view; P. hylactor in (14) dorsal and (15) ventral view; P. jariyae in (16) dorsal and (17) ventral view; P. k r a in (18) dorsal and (19) ventral view; P. tennaserim in (20) dorsal and (21) ventral view; P. tigrina in (22) dorsal and (23) ventral view. Figs. 20 – 21 are of holotype prior to extraction of genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230503/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Fig. 
<number box="[1175,1205,1815,1839]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
), which is narrowly digitate in 
<taxonomicName box="[270,422,1851,1874]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Ptilomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tennaserim">
<emphasis box="[270,422,1851,1874]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">P. tennaserim</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[437,521,1850,1875]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1895]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 23. Terminal abdominal segments of male Ptilomera. P. fang in (10) dorsal and (11) ventral view; P. hemmingseni in (12) dorsal and (13) ventral view; P. hylactor in (14) dorsal and (15) ventral view; P. jariyae in (16) dorsal and (17) ventral view; P. k r a in (18) dorsal and (19) ventral view; P. tennaserim in (20) dorsal and (21) ventral view; P. tigrina in (22) dorsal and (23) ventral view. Figs. 20 – 21 are of holotype prior to extraction of genitalia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230503/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Fig. 
<number box="[490,521,1851,1875]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
). Females of 
<emphasis box="[671,775,1851,1874]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">P. j ar i y ae</emphasis>
can be distinguished by stout, divergent connexival spines with a sharp basal inflection (
<figureCitation box="[501,588,1886,1911]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 37" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1584,1607]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1561]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1563]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 37. Terminal abdominal segments of female Ptilomera. P. fang in (24) dorsal and (25) lateral view; P. hemmingseni in (26) dorsal and (27) lateral view; P. hylactor in (28) dorsal and (29) lateral view; P. j ar i y ae in (30) dorsal and (31) lateral view; P. k r a in (32) dorsal and (33) lateral view; P. tennaserim in (34) dorsal and (35) lateral view; P. tigrina in (36) dorsal and (37) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230504/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">
Fig. 
<number box="[557,588,1887,1911]" pageId="4" pageNumber="105" value="30.0">30</number>
</figureCitation>
), whereas both regional congeners have elongate, convergent connexival spines (
<figureCitation box="[236,373,1922,1947]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 37" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1584,1607]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1561]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,193,1563]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 37. Terminal abdominal segments of female Ptilomera. P. fang in (24) dorsal and (25) lateral view; P. hemmingseni in (26) dorsal and (27) lateral view; P. hylactor in (28) dorsal and (29) lateral view; P. j ar i y ae in (30) dorsal and (31) lateral view; P. k r a in (32) dorsal and (33) lateral view; P. tennaserim in (34) dorsal and (35) lateral view; P. tigrina in (36) dorsal and (37) lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230504/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="105">Figs. 34, 36</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
